 Combined (2014) – Adds the site generated traffic from the proposed office development

One intersection fell below the APFO threshold with the additional site traffic. As such, mitigation
was recommended for this intersection which is described below and shown in Figure ES-3.
Intersection of Carpenter Fire Station Road and Cary Glen Boulevard
This intersection has one movement, the southbound left-turn, operating at LOS F in both the
AM and PM peak periods in the 2014 Combined conditions. This movement operates at LOS
F in the AM peak period and LOS E in the PM peak period in the 2014 Background
conditions. There is also one movement, the southbound shared through and right-turn,
operating at LOS E in the PM peak period in the 2014 Combined conditions. This movement
operates at LOS D in the AM and PM peak periods in the 2014 Background conditions.
Several geometric improvements were considered, such as exclusive turn lanes, but these
did not provide the necessary improvement in delay. Therefore, due to the increase in delay
for a movement operating at LOS F and the degradation of a movement to LOS E, an
evaluation of peak hour signal warrants was performed and is included in Appendix I. The
peak hour warrant evaluation indicates this intersection will meet peak hour warrants in the
2014 Combined scenario. While meeting one signal warrant does not guarantee the
installation of a signal, the intersection was analyzed as a two-phase signalized intersection
in the Combined Improved conditions which resulted in LOS A operations in the AM and PM
peak periods. A full signal warrant analysis should be performed and if warranted, provision
of the signal should be the responsibility of the development.
Table 2 provides a comparison of this intersection in the 2014 Background, 2014 Combined,
and 2014 Combined and Improved conditions. As shown in Table 2, without mitigation the
intersection does not meet the APFO requirements but with the proposed mitigation the
intersection satisfies the requirements of the APFO.

neighborhood of Cary, NC east to NC 55 where it currently ends. In the Town of Cary’s
Comprehensive Transportation Plan (CTP), it is planned to extend McCrimmon Parkway
from NC 55 east to where another section of McCrimmon Parkway intersects with Louis
Stephens Drive. When the connection is made, McCrimmon Parkway will extend to NC

Carpenter Fire Station Road is an east-west connector that is posted 45 mph east of
Yates Store Road and 35 mph west of Yates Store Road and runs from Allforth Place

Peak hour turning movement counts from 7:00-9:00 AM and 4:00-6:00 PM were conducted in
June 2012 for all but one intersection. Turning movement counts for the intersection of
Carpenter Fire Station Road and Cameron Pond Drive were conducted in November 2011
and were provided by the Town of Cary. The count data is located in Appendix C. These
counts were taken to provide current volumes and assist in determining the directional splits
of existing traffic. The count volumes were balanced in areas where appropriate and grown
two years at the determined growth rate (discussed in Section 3.1) to estimate 2014 volumes.
The 2011 counts at Carpenter Fire Station Road and Cameron Pond Drive were performed
near the end of the year in the month of, November. These counts were generally higher
than the study area counts taken in June of this year. Given this information, the volumes at
this intersection were adjusted for balancing purposes and not grown at 4% to estimate 2012
There are two schools, Mills Park Elementary and Mills Park Middle, located on Mills Park
Drive to the south of the proposed site. There is one high school, Panther Creek High
School, located on McCrimmon Parkway to the north of the proposed site. With the
exception of the Carpenter Fire Station Road and Cameron Pond Drive intersection, all
turning movement counts were taken when these schools were not in session. Therefore, the
existing counts were adjusted in order to account for school traffic that would likely be on the
study area roadways during a typical peak hour. Counts taken in May 2012 (when schools
were in session) for several intersections in the study area, including Green Level Church
Road and Courtland View Lane / Mills Park Drive were provided by the Town of Cary in order
to assist in determining the amount of school traffic. The school bell schedules, number of
students and staff at each school and the NCDOT Municipal and School Transportation
Assistance (MSTA) group school trip calculator along with the May 2012 counts, all of which
are provided in Appendix D, were evaluated to determine the appropriate effect of school
traffic. Based on this evaluation, it was determined that traffic generated by the middle school
should be the only school trips added in our analysis. Additionally, based on the bell
schedule, this traffic was only added in the AM peak hour since the peak hour of the turning
movement counts occurs well after the school has released for the day. The calculation and
assignment of school traffic can be found in Appendix D. The volumes that were used in the
analyses are shown on Figure 3 and the volume calculations are located in Appendix D.

 The peak hour factor for the southbound left-turn, eastbound through movement,

peak period based upon the peaking characteristics of school traffic due to the fact

afternoon peak does not align with the roadway PM peak period.

analysis. There were also additional trips added to account for approved developments that

The TAR that was conducted for Parkside Town Commons had an estimated completion
date of 2009 and proposed a site that consists of 740,000 square feet of shopping center,
230,000 square feet of office space, 350 apartments, and 100 condominiums/townhomes.
However, there has been no construction to date. Based on discussions with Town of
Cary staff, there are ongoing negotiations with the developer and it is possible that the
overall plan of the development may change prior to construction. The development
currently has an approved site plan until 2014. Therefore, site trips shown in the TAR will
be added to the background traffic and included in this analysis. There are no common
intersections with the two TARs, but the Parkside Town Commons TAR assigns some site
traffic to McCrimmon Parkway. The Parkside Town Commons site traffic will be added to
McCrimmon Parkway in this TAR and distributed through the network as appropriate.
The Evan’s Farm Update is an amendment to a previous analysis in 2002 for the Evan’s
Farm Development. The update consists of an additional 208 townhomes located in the
southeast quadrant of O’Kelly Chapel Road and Green Level Church Road. A portion of
the additional development traffic was assigned to the Green Level Church Road and
McCrimmon Parkway intersection. Therefore site trips from this development will be
added to the background traffic and included in this analysis. The site traffic will be added
to the Green Level Church Road and McCrimmon Parkway intersection as shown in TAR
167A and distributed through the other study intersections as appropriate.
The Cameron Pond Update is an amendment to the analysis done for the existing
Cameron Pond neighborhood. The update consists of an additional 15 home sites and is
located on Carpenter Fire Station Road to the east of the study area for this analysis.
Therefore, site traffic from the additional Cameron Pond development will be added to the
background traffic and included in this analysis.

As previously discussed, the proposed development is located within the Town of Cary’s Base
Benefit Zone and therefore recommendations will be based on a level of service standard of “D”.
Parcel TC-3A of the Cary Park Development is proposed to consist of 20,000 square feet of
office space. An existing right-in/right-out driveway on Carpenter Fire Station Road currently
serving a veterinary hospital is proposed to be relocated approximately 100 feet to the west.
Upon the completion of the Parcel TC-3A development, this relocated driveway will provide a
consolidated right-in/right-out access off of Carpenter Fire Station Road for both the new
office development and the veterinary hospital. Trip generation rates were used from the ITE
Edition to determine the amount of trips the site would generate.
The trip generation summary is shown in Table 6 below.
Access to the development is proposed to be provided via a relocated right-in/right-out
driveway on Carpenter Fire Station Road as described in section 4.1 above. Trip distribution
was estimated based on count data from nearby intersections, and from knowledge of local
trip attractions and destinations in the area. The site distribution percentages are shown on
Figure 7 and the site trips are shown on Figure 8. The trip generation and distribution
calculations are located in Appendix D.
The Combined (2014) scenario consists of the background with approved development traffic
as discussed in Section 3.0 of this TAR plus the site generated trips from the proposed office
development on Parcel TC-3A. The volumes that are used in the Combined (2014) analysis
are shown in Figure 9. The laneage used for the 2014 Combined scenario is based on the
existing laneage provided by Figure 3 with the extension of the shared northbound through
and right-turn lane at the intersection of Green Level Church Road and Courtland View
lane/Mills Park Drive and the addition of driveway modifications provided by the site plan,
Since there are no new intersections provided by the development of Cary Park Parcel TC-
3A, level of service analyses were performed for all existing intersections with the
modifications as noted above. A summary of the levels of service are found in Tables 7a –

Based on the 2014 Combined analyses, one unsignalized intersection has two movements
that operate below the LOS D threshold for the Base Benefit Transportation Zone. The
southbound left-turn movement for the Carpenter Fire Station and Cary Glen Boulevard
intersection operates at LOS F in both the AM and PM peak periods while the southbound
through and right-turn movement operates at LOS E in the PM peak period. The results
provided in Table 7c indicate that both movements experience an increase in delay when
compared to the background analyses. Based on Section 3.23.3 of the LDO, at unsignalized
intersections no movements are allowed to fall below the LOS D threshold or experience an
increase in delay for movements that already operate below the LOS D threshold for the
Base Benefit Transportation Zone. Therefore, this intersection will require additional
mitigation to meet the APFO. The mitigation is evaluated and described in Section 4.4. The
2014 Combined analyses are located in Appendix H.

Combined (2014) Improved Level of Service Analysis
The Combined (2014) Improved scenario consists of improvements identified as mitigations
that are proposed in order to meet the LOS D threshold or show no increase in overall
intersection delay if the intersection operates below LOS D in the background condition as
noted in Section 4.3. The intersections requiring mitigation are listed below, along with the
proposed mitigation. The 2014 Combined with Improvements Synchro analyses are located
Intersection of Carpenter Fire Station Road and Cary Glen Boulevard
This intersection has one movement, the southbound left-turn, operating at LOS F in both the
AM and PM peak periods in the 2014 Combined conditions. This movement operates at LOS
F in the AM peak period and LOS E in the PM peak period in the 2014 Background
conditions. There is also one movement, the southbound through and right-turn, operating at
LOS E in the PM peak period in the 2014 Combined conditions. This movement operates at
LOS D in the AM and PM peak periods in the 2014 Background conditions. Several
geometric improvements were considered, such as exclusive turn lanes, but these did not
provide the necessary improvement in delay. Therefore, due to the increase in delay for a
movement operating at LOS F and the degradation of a movement to LOS E, an evaluation
of peak hour signal warrants was performed and is included in Appendix I. The peak hour
warrant evaluation indicates this intersection will meet peak hour warrants in the 2014
Combined scenario. While meeting one signal warrant does not guarantee the installation of
a signal, the intersection was analyzed as a two-phase signalized intersection in the
Combined Improved conditions which resulted in LOS A operations in the AM and PM peak
periods. A full signal warrant analysis should be performed and if warranted, provision of the
signal should be the responsibility of the development.
